	" Classes and goals
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"Take note of each of the following pages for 
	(__wikiLink|displaytext=classes|href=/Class)
	", as they contain the most up-to-date information what goals are acceptable under them:
	$LF
]div
[ul 
	[li 
		" 
		(__wikiLink|href=/Standard|implicitdisplaytext=Standard)
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" 
		(__wikiLink|href=/Alternative|implicitdisplaytext=Alternative)
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" 
		(__wikiLink|href=/Playground|implicitdisplaytext=Playground)
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[div class=p 
	"Make sure branch labels are accurate. Ask other staff, particularly 
	(__wikiLink|displaytext=Publishers|href=/Publishing)
	", for advice on this if need be. "any%" labels can be removed for redundancy.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"After having approved the goal of the movie, it'd help Publishers a lot if you also 
	(__wikiLink|displaytext=catalog the submission|href=/EncodingGuide/PublicationManual#CatalogueTheSubmission)
	" while you still have all the files required for syncing it.
	$LF
]div
[hr 
]hr
[h3 id=ImprovementsAndObsoletions 
	" Improvements and obsoletions
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"A new movie may involve 
	[b 
		"emulation accuracy
	]b
	" improvements, which often adds extra lag, resulting in improvements that appear longer than the movie they're trying to obsolete. Always ensure the new movie has gameplay improvements. If the new timesavers can be applied to the old movie, they count as improvements.
	$LF
]div
[hr 
]hr
[h3 id=MajorSkipGlitches 
	" Major skip glitches
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	(__wikiLink|displaytext=Major skip glitches|href=/MovieTagGuidelines#MajorSkipGlitch)
	" (sometimes called 
	(__wikiLink|displaytext=game-breaking glitches|href=/Glossary#GameBreakingGlitch)
	") require additional confirmation that it's actually a developer oversight, and 
	(__wikiLink|displaytext=not a cheat code or a password|href=/MovieRules#GameplayMustBeAccurateToHardware)
	" that's subtly entered and looks like a glitched skip.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"The most certain way to determine this is reading what programming code the game is executing, but there are some trends among cheat code scenarios that can make this detection easier:
	$LF
]div
[ol 
	[li 
		" Input that works specifically during pause screens, menu screens, or other non-gameplay-based input
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Buttons have effects that have nothing to do with what the button normally does in gameplay or in menus
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Doing certain steps a number of times, or entering certain button combinations ("jump 10 times then press B+Select")
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Easy and consistent to replicate if you know the steps
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Increments or decrements memory values in consistent steps, especially if not related to normal gameplay functions (see also point 2)
		$LF
	]li
]ol
[hr 
]hr
[h3 id=GameCompletionPoint 
	" Game completion point
	$LF
]h3
[h4 id=GlitchedEndings 
	" Glitched endings
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"Runs that incorporate "game end glitch" techniques need certain verification on whether the ending really occurs. It can be done by comparing how the game acts after it ended normally with how it acts after it was glitch-ended.
	$LF
]div
[h4 id=PostCompletionInput 
	" Post-completion input
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"Manually ensure the game has fully ended. For example, after the game reaches some screen that does not seem to automatically fade out nor lead to the game start again, save a state and try pressing a few buttons to see if it's possible to proceed further (switch to recording if needed).
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Sometimes extra input is required after the game's ending sequence has started, so it can fully proceed to the last ending screen. It is preferred to contain such input in the submitted movie, but exceptions can be made and an extended movie can be used for encoding.
	$LF
]div
[hr 
]hr
[h3 id=EditingTheSubmissions 
	" Editing the submissions
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"Apply the 
	(__wikiLink|href=/EditorGuidelines|implicitdisplaytext=Editor Guidelines)
	" to your editions. Specifically:
	$LF
]div
[ul 
	[li 
		" Do not delete text written by others.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Use clear, easy to read markup and language.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Attribute clearly.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[div class=p 
	"When you edit a submission, your markup should look something like this:
	$LF
]div
[pre 
	[code 
		$UNPRINTABLE TEXT!!!
	]code
]pre
[div class=p 
	"(
	[code 
		"420M
	]code
	" (an example) stands for a link to 
	(__wikiLink|displaytext=publication 420|href=/420M)
	".)
	$LF
]div
[hr 
]hr
[h3 id=ReplacingSubmissionFiles 
	" Replacing submission files
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"Judges have the ability to replace a submission file. This can be done when the submitter finds a small improvement to their submission; it is usually better to incorporate it immediately rather than cancel and submit a new movie. Before replacing, check that the movie still satisfies its stated goals and that the movie file still syncs.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Use this feature only for 
	[em 
		"small
	]em
	" improvements and not major changes. Anything that could possibly invalidate the voting results should definitely be a new submission (such as a controversial trick, a major improvement, or anything that might affect the entertainment value of the movie).
	$LF
]div
[hr 
]hr
[h3 id=ImprovingTheSubmissionYouReJudging 
	" Improving the submission you're judging
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"Sometimes a judge may come up with a complete improvement and even become a co-author. There's no hard line on how exactly to handle it, but there are two basic options:
	$LF
]div
[ul 
	[li 
		" If you've fixed a minor issue without investing too much effort (like trimming blank input at the end, or starting the game a bit sooner), just replace the submission with your updated movie and continue judging
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" If you've improved actual gameplay and it was non-trivial, you need to reset the submission to "New", post the improvement for submission replacement, and request co-autorship (or you may replace the file right away and add yourself). Another judge will handle all the rest.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[hr 
]hr
[h3 id=Procedures 
	" Procedures
	$LF
]h3
[h4 id=Judging_2 
	" Judging
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"When you're about to handle a submission, set it to 
	[em 
		""judging underway"
	]em
	" so other judges know it is already being taken care of. If you feel strongly about judging a particular submission that someone else has claimed, ask them politely and they will most likely hand it over to you.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"A submission must be in the queue for 72 hours before a verdict can be made. This allows for the audience to provide critical feedback. The audience has a say, so let them say it, and give the author a sufficient chance to respond to them. Let active conversations play out, and contribute to them with your own thoughts.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Avoid making blanket statements like "this section looks improvable". Instead, ask the author why they did that section in the way they did, or take the time to show that section 
	[b 
		"IS
	]b
	" improvable. Show an existing WIP, or make a short one of your own.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"If you expect some people to be unhappy about the verdict you are leaning to, communicate your thoughts and options in a post and discuss them as well. Your decision should ideally reflect a consensus and feel understandable, especially for the author(s).
	$LF
]div
[h4 id=Reviews 
	" Reviews
	$LF
]h4
[ul 
	[li 
		" A 
		(__wikiLink|displaytext=Reviewer|href=/Judging#Reviewers)
		" checks which submissions are unclaimed or need research, and makes a review forum post, adding themselves to 
		(__wikiLink|displaytext=the Reviews wiki list|href=/Reviews)
		".
		$LF
		[ul 
			[li 
				" A Reviewer can also review 
				(__wikiLink|displaytext=rejected submissions that may now be acceptable|href=/Forum/Topics/22780)
				" under 
				(__wikiLink|displaytext=rule changes|href=/MovieRules/History)
				".
				$LF
			]li
		]ul
	]li
	[li 
		" The review doesn't need to cover 
		(__wikiLink|displaytext=100% of the aspects|href=/MovieRules)
		" that a judgment covers. Here's a list of the most meaningful individual verification tasks, a review may opt to verify just one of them, or an arbitrary number of them:
		$LF
		[ul 
			[li 
				" Replayability (sync) of the submission, ideally coupled with 
				(__wikiLink|href=/Cataloging|implicitdisplaytext=cataloging)
				" it
				$LF
			]li
			[li 
				" 
				(__wikiLink|displaytext=Goal choice|href=/MovieRules#GoalChoice)
				": which class the goal belongs to, and whether it's fulfilled in the movie
				$LF
			]li
			[li 
				" 
				(__wikiLink|displaytext=Optimality|href=/JudgeGuidelines#EnsureTheMovieIsOptimized)
				$LF
			]li
		]ul
	]li
	[li 
		" A Judge waits with the claiming before actually starting working on a submission (to let Reviewers know which submissions they are free to review), then checks the 
		(__wikiLink|href=/Reviews|implicitdisplaytext=Reviews)
		" list and uses existing reviews for that submission in the judgment.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" In the decision, the Judge addresses which parts of the review were correct and which weren't, so Reviewers could better learn how to approach submissions, but without getting intimidated by criticism.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Upon judging, the Judge removes the submission from 
		(__wikiLink|displaytext=the wiki list|href=/Reviews)
		".
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" If one wants to review a claimed movie, they just make a regular post without adding themselves into the Reviews list.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[hr 
]hr
[h3 id=WhenYouReDone 
	" When you're done
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"Even after you've finished judging a movie, a judge's job doesn't necessarily stop there.
	$LF
]div
[ul 
	[li 
		" Communicate with viewers who have questions regarding your judgment.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Communicate with the publisher and assist them as necessary.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Communicate with other judges who need to judge a different submission for the game if they have any questions.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" If it was revealed you made a mistake in your judgment, first of all, don't beat yourself up, everyone makes mistakes.
		$LF
		[ul 
			[li 
				" Any mistake other than those which resulted in a published movie is fixable.
				$LF
				[ul 
					[li 
						" If the movie was already published, speak to the other staff, maybe someone has a creative solution. If not, it happens, revel in your ability to be human.
						$LF
					]li
				]ul
			]li
			[li 
				" Learn from your mistakes for next time.
				$LF
			]li
		]ul
	]li
]ul
